WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:27.520
I like stuff. I like this, and I like this, and I like this.

00:27.520 --> 00:29.760
I like stuff, and I want more stuff.

00:31.200 --> 00:36.160
My child, hearken to my voice. It is I, Socrates.

00:36.160 --> 00:38.080
Oh no. What do you want?

00:38.080 --> 00:40.480
I haven't seen you at the symposium of late.

00:41.040 --> 00:44.880
Well yeah, because you kind of hate women, and it was getting me down.

00:44.880 --> 00:49.280
My child, without my guidance you have become a slave to mere appetite.

00:49.280 --> 00:52.960
Have you forgotten what I've taught you about the true meaning of happiness,

00:52.960 --> 00:55.840
the rational contemplation of truth and justice?

00:56.560 --> 01:00.560
Look, I tried that, and honestly, I don't think it's really my thing.

01:00.560 --> 01:03.280
I'm a dum-dum, and I like shiny things.

01:03.280 --> 01:06.880
Ach, but my child, these are pleasures for the pigs.

01:06.880 --> 01:11.200
Happiness can only be acquired through the contemplation of beauty itself,

01:11.200 --> 01:15.440
perfectly exemplified in the supple bodies of young boys.

01:16.000 --> 01:19.600
Okay, thank you for your feedback. We'll take that into consideration.

01:20.400 --> 01:21.920
Ugh, Greeks.

01:21.920 --> 01:27.680
Look, we all have wants, needs, desires, and we all want happiness.

01:27.680 --> 01:31.280
But happiness, what does that word even mean?

01:31.280 --> 01:33.680
I'm just a dum-dum who likes shiny things,

01:33.680 --> 01:36.640
and these are questions really better left to the philosophers,

01:36.640 --> 01:39.920
which is why I'm not going to present my original ideas in this video.

01:39.920 --> 01:43.120
Instead, I will be interpreting one of the most influential works

01:43.120 --> 01:45.840
of anti-capitalist philosophy ever produced,

01:45.840 --> 01:48.960
a series in multiple volumes that examines deeply

01:48.960 --> 01:51.280
the concept of the fetishism of the commodity.

01:51.280 --> 01:55.360
I am of course talking about Worth It, a series on BuzzFeed Video

01:55.360 --> 01:58.480
about three men who are younger than me who travel the world

01:58.480 --> 02:01.520
and try different foods that cost different amounts of money,

02:01.520 --> 02:04.640
and then say whether it was worth it.

02:04.640 --> 02:08.080
In each episode, they taste a type of food at three different restaurants

02:08.080 --> 02:10.160
at three drastically different price points

02:10.160 --> 02:12.960
to find out which one is the most worth it.

02:12.960 --> 02:18.720
For example, they compare a $2 pizza to a $2,000 pizza that's made of gold,

02:18.720 --> 02:23.600
and a $1 ice cream to a $1,000 ice cream that's made of gold,

02:23.600 --> 02:27.840
and a $1 bagel to a $1,000 bagel that's made of gold.

02:27.840 --> 02:28.960
It is a lot of gold.

02:28.960 --> 02:30.640
What do I do with the gold on my fingers?

02:30.640 --> 02:31.760
A gonjapreneur!

02:31.760 --> 02:36.480
Now to the untrained eye, Worth It may seem like insipid YouTube click fodder,

02:36.480 --> 02:38.720
but we intellectuals, well,

02:38.720 --> 02:41.520
we have a taste for insights that penetrate a little deeper.

02:41.520 --> 02:43.760
We like to take it all in.

02:43.760 --> 02:44.480
Ah!

02:44.480 --> 02:47.440
The Worth It Boys, Andrew, Adam, Stephen,

02:48.240 --> 02:50.400
these are not mere content creators,

02:50.400 --> 02:54.320
mere actors, dancing monkeys performing for ad revenue.

02:54.320 --> 02:57.600
They're philosophers, spiritual leaders even,

02:57.600 --> 03:00.720
and what they've accomplished on YouTube, quite honestly,

03:00.720 --> 03:04.800
far surpasses the combined insights of Marx, Engels, Lenin,

03:04.800 --> 03:08.480
Sartre, Trotsky, Luxembourg, Gramsci, LukÃ¡cs,

03:08.480 --> 03:12.080
Zarathustra, and even our dear bread mom Kropotkin.

03:12.080 --> 03:15.600
I've of course read each of these great thinkers' complete works many,

03:15.600 --> 03:18.400
many times, but I always come away dissatisfied,

03:18.400 --> 03:20.720
and I find myself returning, yet again,

03:20.720 --> 03:24.320
to the unparalleled masterworks of Andrew, Adam, and Steve.

03:24.320 --> 03:28.960
See, each episode of Worth It poses to the viewer a fundamental question.

03:28.960 --> 03:30.640
Is it worth it?

03:30.640 --> 03:31.760
We may never know.

03:31.760 --> 03:36.880
Take, for instance, the case of the $2 pizza versus the $2,000 gold pizza.

03:36.880 --> 03:38.720
Which is the better deal?

03:38.720 --> 03:42.400
I mean, how would we even begin to answer such a perplexing riddle?

03:42.400 --> 03:44.000
Well, according to Karl Marx,

03:44.000 --> 03:47.360
the value of a commodity must be understood in two ways.

03:47.360 --> 03:49.680
On the one hand, there's the use value,

03:49.680 --> 03:53.040
the commodity's capacity to satisfy some human need.

03:53.040 --> 03:56.000
And on the other hand, there is the exchange value,

03:56.000 --> 03:59.920
the quantity determining the ratio by which a commodity is exchangeable

03:59.920 --> 04:01.680
with every other commodity,

04:01.680 --> 04:06.400
deriving from objectified labor over time and expressed in terms of price.

04:06.400 --> 04:08.320
But let's not oversimplify things.

04:08.320 --> 04:11.520
Clearly, Andrew, Adam, and Steve are inviting us,

04:11.520 --> 04:13.360
the viewers of Worth It,

04:13.360 --> 04:17.200
to understand the use-value-exchange-value dichotomy

04:17.200 --> 04:19.840
not as a mere hierarchical binary,

04:19.840 --> 04:22.720
but as a sort of Deleuzian rhizome,

04:22.720 --> 04:27.040
a non-arborescent multiplicity with as many sinuous interconnections

04:27.040 --> 04:29.280
as the truffles on the pizza itself.

04:29.280 --> 04:30.880
Am I making myself clear?

04:30.880 --> 04:31.440
I'm not.

04:31.440 --> 04:35.120
It's almost as if the philosophers are simply burdening me with jargon

04:35.120 --> 04:37.520
and not actually helping me think through this any better.

04:37.520 --> 04:42.640
So, let's throw philosophy in the trash and start over from the beginning.

04:42.640 --> 04:43.280
Fuck this!

04:52.080 --> 04:55.200
I like stuff, and I like shiny things.

04:55.200 --> 04:57.200
Now that's something everyone can understand,

04:57.200 --> 05:00.640
so let's take that as the first axiom of the economic theory

05:00.640 --> 05:02.320
I'll be developing in this video.

05:02.320 --> 05:06.000
So, given that I like stuff and I like shiny things,

05:06.000 --> 05:07.440
let's return to the question.

05:07.440 --> 05:10.080
Is a $2,000 pizza worth it?

05:10.080 --> 05:15.040
Well, it is covered in gold, and gold is shiny, so I do like that.

05:15.040 --> 05:18.400
But the pizza itself seems kind of gross.

05:18.400 --> 05:21.280
It's got squid ink dough smeared with foie gras,

05:21.280 --> 05:25.360
stilton cheese, black truffles, gold flakes, and caviar.

05:25.360 --> 05:28.880
These flavors are overwhelming and they don't make any sense together.

05:28.880 --> 05:32.240
The only thing they have in common is being really expensive.

05:32.240 --> 05:35.520
